{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473343"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:07:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:07:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2359"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2359"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.01,0.74,0.01,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"21797"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2359"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10704"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1461"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"21797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/21797"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 1-week-old boy is brought to the physician due to swollen scrotum. He was born at term. The pregnancy was complicated by pre-eclampsia that was controlled with anti-hypertensive drugs. The delivery was uncomplicated. On genital examination, there is a significantly swollen scrotum. The testes are palpable and are not felt separately from the swelling. The spermatic cord can be palpated. A transillumination test is positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the best next step in the management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aspiration of the fluid","Karyotype analysis","Reassurance","Surgical removal of testes","Surgical repair"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe swollen scrotum is the result of a hydrocele. A hydrocele is a congenital disorder characterised by an accumulation of fluid around the scrotum. It can be differentiated from other potential diagnoses by clinical examination. The testes are not felt separately from the swelling and the spermatic cord is easily palpable. A transillumination test is typically positive in hydrocele. In cases in which diagnosis is uncertain, a scrotal ultrasound can be performed to confirm the diagnosis. Patients are mostly asymptomatic. The management of any hydrocele depends on the age of the patient. Patients aged \u0026lt;2 years old can be treated conservatively, observed and the parents \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassured\u003C/strong\u003E, since in most cases the hydrocele will self-resolve. However, in patients aged \u0026gt;2 years, surgical repair should be carried out to prevent complications associated with a hydrocele (eg, incarcerated indirect inguinal hernia, infertility).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgical repair is recommended in patients who have a persistent hydrocele after 2 years of age. This patient is 1 week old, and his hydrocele will most likely resolve spontaneously.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspiration of the fluid through needle aspiration is not recommended since most likely the fluid will reaccumulate. In addition, needle aspiration increases the risk of seeding of the scrotum with infectious pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKaryotype analysis is performed in patients with ambiguous genitalia. A hydrocele is not associated with karyotype abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESurgical removal of the testes is performed in patients who are suspected to have testicular cancer. Testicular tumours are unlikely in a newborn patient. In addition, a testicular tumour presents with a firm or hard swelling in the testis and is not transilluminated. This patient is unlikely to have testicular cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hydroceles in young children (aged under two) do not need any form of intervention."],"references":["Acer-Demir T, Ekenci B, \u00d6zer D, Turano\u011flu M, Haberal K, Bilgin E et al. Natural History and Conservative Treatment Outcomes for Hydroceles: A Retrospective Review of One Center\u0027s Experience. Urology. 2018;112:155-160.","Naji H, Ingolfsson I, Isacson D, Svensson J. Decision making in the management of hydroceles in infants and children. European Journal of Pediatrics. 2011;171(5):807-810."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10704"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2359"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"10704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/10704"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-03-22T21:14:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-03-22T21:14:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2359"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"21797"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21